# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gb/ac] The **.ac** top-level domain is the Internet country code (ccTLD) for Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha, used primarily for Ascension Island (Saint Helena has its own ccTLD, .sh).
[src:gb/ac] It is administered by NIC.AC, a subsidiary of the Afilias-owned company Internet Computer Bureau.
[src:gb/ac] Registration for the domain is open to anyone.
[src:gb/ac] The registry accepts registrations of internationalised domain names.
[src:gb/ad] .ad was originally only for Andorran registrants or trademark holders and each registration had to be pre-approved.
[src:gb/ad] In 2024 the registry relaunched the TLD and revised all policies.
[src:gb/ad] Since 22 May 2024 it is a requirement to use an accredited registrar.
[src:gb/ad] Before that date, registrants could buy domains directly from the registry, which was discontinued.
[src:gb/ad] Since 22 October 2024 the registration policies were changed so that any natural or legal person worldwide can register a domain name under .ad.
[src:gb/ad] Additionally, domains are not subject to prior validation anymore and are instead processed immediately.
[src:gb/ad] Registrars outside of Andorra are also able to accredit themselves since then.
[src:gb/ad] Because .ad is an abbreviation for the word advertisement or advert, .ad has also been used in an unconventional manner as a domain hack by some advertising media.
[src:gb/ae] The internationalised country code top-level domain in the Arabic alphabet of the UAE is امارات., which is romanised as emarat.
[src:gb/ae] It is represented as `.xn--mgbaam7a8h` in Punycode.
[src:gb/ae] The domain `ae` is administered by the Telecommunications and Digital Government Regulatory Authority (TDRA) of the UAE.
[src:gb/ae] Registrations are permitted directly at the second level (unrestricted zone) or at the third level (restricted zone) beneath several category labels.
[src:gb/ae] During 2008 when ae was re-delegated to the TRA, the .aeDA published new policies in which co.ae was introduced only for local commercial companies provided that the name is connected to the business name.
[src:gb/ae] The .AE domain was originally delegated to UUNET.
[src:gb/ae] Recognising the domain should be administered in the country, the domain was transferred in 1995 to Etisalat, following a brief period of administration by the United Arab Emirates University.
[src:gb/ae] Since that time, Etisalat, through its division the UAE Network Information Center (UAEnic), has been responsible for the operation of the .ae domain.
[src:gb/ae] During GITEX 2006, TDRA announced that the .ae ccTLD management and operations will be re-delegated to TDRA from Etisalat/UAEnic, the current .ae ccTLD manager.
[src:gb/ae] A new entity called .ae Domain Administration (.aeDA) has been formed to take care of management and operations of .ae based on latest DNS and Domain Registry technologies.
[src:gb/ae] During January 2008, IANA officially re-delegated the .ae Domain to the TDRA.
[src:gb/ae] On 3 August 2008, the .aeDA took over the DNS and launched their services with the new registry system which supports registry–registrar model.
[src:gb/ae] Currently the .aeDA has accredited eight registrars from different parts of the world.
[src:gb/ae] For the first time, Internet users in the UAE will be able to register and manage their domain names under .ae automatically using an online system without going through manual process which used to take up to six weeks for domain registrations.
[src:gb/ae] As per .aeDA policies, current domain holders are allowed to transfer between registrars at no cost.
[src:gb/ae] .ae was the first ccTLD in the Arab region to use the standard Registry-Registrar model.
[src:gb/ae] As well, .aeDA is the first registry in the region to use the industry-standard Extensible Provisioning Protocol to manage its domains.
[src:gb/ae] Registrants (domain name holders) can transfer their domains from one registrar to another provided that they obtain a domain name password.
[src:gb/ae] Domain name passwords can be recovered online through .aeDA's website password-recovery.aeda.net.ae.
[src:gb/ae] After obtaining this password, registrants can supply this password to the gaining registrar who will be able to transfer it directly without dealing with the losing registrar.
[src:gb/ae] Losing registrars are prohibited from charging a fee when a domain transfer occur; however gaining registrars may do so.
[src:gb/ae] .ae domain name retail prices ranges from 30 USD to 200 USD depending on the provider and the level of support and services provided with the domain name.
[src:gb/ae] The .ae registration prices have noticeably dropped since the introduction of .aeDA.
[src:gb/ae] Prior to 3 August 2008, .ae domains were offered by Etisalat for around 41 USD per year while ac.ae, org.ae, gov.ae and sch.ae were offered for around 20 USD per year.
[src:gb/ae] International providers used to charge around 100–200 USD in order to cover the administrative cost involved in the manual registration process.
[src:gb/ae] After .aeDA's go-live in August 2008, .ae registration price declined to as low as 30 USD with international registrars.
[src:gb/ae] On 16-Sep-2012 aeDA made an announcement on reaching the 100,000 registration mark in domain names.
[src:gb/ae] During Gitex2008, .aeDA domain name counter showed over 90,000 domain names currently held in the registry, making it the largest ccTLD registry in the Arab region.
[src:gb/ae] As of May 2023, there are more than 300,000+ domains in the zone.
[src:gb/ae] 35 (21–26 June 2009) in Sydney, .aeDA representatives mentioned that aeDA's EPP-based registry system is fully compatible with IDN protocols and guidelines.
[src:gb/ae] In January 2010 ICANN announced that the UAE IDN ccTLD (DNS name: xn—mgbaam7a8h, امارات) was one of the first four new IDN ccTLDs to have passed the Fast Track String Evaluation within the domain application process.
[src:gb/ae] .aeDA, the registry operator of .ae is also the official operator for UAE ENUM Space (971).
[src:gb/ae] The ENUM space was redelegated from the incumbent operator Etisalat since 16 April 2009.
[src:gb/af] The .af domain was delegated to Abdul Razeeq in 1997, a year after Taliban fighters had captured Kabul and founded the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan.
[src:gb/af] NetNames of London initially maintained the domain following an agreement with the IANA.
[src:gb/af] Razeeq later disappeared, halting some services.
[src:gb/af] The domain was reopened on 10 March 2003, as a joint program between UNDP and the Afghan Ministry of Communications.
[src:gb/af] As of 26 August 2020, .af was used by 5,960 domains.
[src:gb/af] With the fall of Kabul in 2021, the .af domain again came under the control of the Taliban.
[src:gb/af] ICANN said it "defers decision making to within the country".
[src:gb/af] Registration is made directly at the second level, or on the third level beneath various categorised subdomains at the second level.
[src:gb/af] Third-level domains have restrictions based on which second-level domain they are registered under.
[src:gb/af] Registration on the second level is unrestricted, but more expensive.
[src:gb/af] All fees are higher for international registrants.
[src:gb/af] In 2024, a number of .af domains including "broke.af" and "queer.af" went offline.
[src:gb/af] The Afghan Ministry of Communications and IT said that they were registered through Gandi, a France-based domain name registrar, and cited Gandi's failure to make payments as the reason for suspension.
[src:gb/ag] There are no restrictions on who can register.
[src:gb/ag] In addition to its original intended use as a country code, the .ag domain has been marketed for use for agriculture-related sites, and for sites referencing the atomic symbol for silver, *Ag*.
[src:gb/ag] It also has a potential use for other domain hacks for English words that end in -ag.
[src:gb/ag] The Heritage Foundation uses .ag for URL shortening (herit.ag), as well as The Association of Former Students of Texas A&M University (tx.ag).
[src:gb/ag] The term is used in Germany, Austria, and Switzerland, but not Liechtenstein or Luxembourg.
[src:gb/ag] Zivilsenat des Oberlandesgerichtes Hamburg*) ruled in July 2004 that a *.ag* domain may only be registered by an *Aktiengesellschaft*, and then only by an AG that has the same name as the domain.
[src:gb/ag] For example, a company with shareholders in Germany having the name X AG may not register as y.ag.
[src:gb/ag] The newspaper Sermitsiaq uses the TLD since its merger with the paper Atuagagdliutit/Grønlandsposten, which was marketed as AG as an abbreviation of its combined Greenlandic and Danish names, thus implying a continuation of its identity.
[src:gb/ai] It is a popular domain hack with companies and projects related to the artificial intelligence industry (AI).
[src:gb/ai] In 2021, Google Search analyst Gary Illyes announced that ".ai" had been added to Google’s list of generic country-code top-level domains, meaning that Google would no longer infer Anguilla-specific targeting from the ccTLD.
[src:gb/ai] Identity Digital began managing the domain as of January 2025.
[src:gb/ai] Registrations within **off.ai**, **com.ai**, **net.ai**, and **org.ai** are available worldwide without restriction.
[src:gb/ai] From 15 September 2009, second level registrations within **.ai** are available to everyone worldwide.
[src:gb/ai] The minimum registration term allowed for .ai domains is 2 through 10 years for registration and renewal, and a 2-year renewal for domain transfer.
[src:gb/ai] Identity Digital is the authority in charge of managing this extension.
[src:gb/ai] Registrations began on 16 February 1995.
[src:gb/ai] The limits on the number of characters used for the domain name are, at a minimum, from 1 to 3, depending on the registrar, and always at most 63 characters.
[src:gb/ai] The character set supported for .ai domain names includes A–Z, a–z, 0–9, and hyphen.
[src:gb/ai] As of November 2022, .ai domains cannot accommodate IDN characters.
[src:gb/ai] There are no requirements for registering a domain, including local and foreign residents.
[src:gb/ai] A .ai domain can be suspended or revoked, if the domain is involved in illegal activity such as violating trademarks or copyrights.
[src:gb/ai] Usage must not violate the laws of Anguilla.
[src:gb/ai] Filing a UDRP challenge requires using one of the ICANN Approved Dispute Resolution Service Providers.
[src:gb/ai] If the domain is with an ICANN accredited registrar, they should work with the arbitrator.
[src:gb/ai] Usually this means either doing nothing or transferring a domain. .ai domains are transferable to any desired registrars as the registration of domain is done maintaining EPP.
[src:gb/ai] There used to be a whois.ai-based platform of expired domains in which those could be procured and auctioned every ten days through a standard online process.
[src:gb/ai] The last auctions of such kind closed there in December 2024; the platform had been scheduled for shutdown on 30 June 2025, but remained online in the months following that date.
[src:gb/ai] Domains cost depends on the registrar, with yearly fees ranging from US$140 (the base fee, as established by Anguilla) to $200.
[src:gb/ai] As of July 2025, the highest-valued .ai domain is an undisclosed one sold on 8 November 2023, on Escrow.com, for US$1,500,000—months after an initial $300,000 sale to the same buyer.
[src:gb/ai] Among the publicly disclosed ones, the most valued, *fin.ai*, was sold for $1,000,000 in March 2025.
[src:gb/ai] On 16 December 2017, the .ai registry started supporting the Extensible Provisioning Protocol (EPP) and migrated all of its domains onto an EPP system.
[src:gb/ai] Consequently, many registrars are allowed to sell .ai domains.
[src:gb/ai] Since that date, the .ai ccTLD has also been popular with artificial intelligence companies and organisations.
[src:gb/ai] Though such trends are primarily seen among new AI based companies or startups, many established AI and Tech companies preferred not to opt for .ai domains.
[src:gb/ai] For example, DeepMind has its domain retained at .com; Meta has redirected its facebook.ai domain to ai.meta.com.
[src:gb/ai] The registration fees earned from the .ai domains go to the treasury of the Government of Anguilla.
[src:gb/ai] As per a 2018 *New York Times* report, the total revenue generated out of selling .ai domains was $2.9 million.
[src:gb/ai] In 2023, Anguilla's government made about US$32 million from fees collected for registering .ai domains; that amounted to over 10% of gross domestic product for the territory.
[src:gb/ai] "In the years before the real breakthrough of AI, revenue from .ai domains made up less than 1% of our state income, by 2025 it will be around 47%," explained Jose Vanterpool, Minister of Infrastructure and Communications (MICUHITES), in an interview with BBC.
[src:gb/ai] The high 90% renewal rate of .ai domains and the 2025 renewal wave of domains registered in 2023 are driving another surge in state revenues, according to Domaintechnik.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The **Gerber format** is an open, ASCII, vector format for printed circuit board (PCB) designs.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It is the *de facto* standard used by PCB industry software to describe the printed circuit board images: copper layers, solder mask, legend, drill data, etc.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The standard file extension is `.GBR` or `.gbr` though other extensions like `.GB`, `.geb` or `.gerber` are also used.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It is documented by The Gerber Layer Format Specification and some related (but less universally supported) extensions such as XNC drill files and GerberJob to convey information about the entire PCB, as opposed to single layers.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] PCBs are designed on a specialized electronic design automation (EDA) or a computer-aided design (CAD) system.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The CAD systems output PCB fabrication data to allow fabrication of the board.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This data typically contains a Gerber file for each image layer (copper layers, solder mask, legend or silk...).
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Gerber is also the standard image input format for all bare board fabrication equipment needing image data, such as photoplotters, legend printers, direct imagers or automated optical inspection (AOI) machines and for viewing reference images in different departments.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] For assembly the fabrication data contains the solder paste layers and the central locations of components to create the stencil and place and bond the components.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The official website contains the specification, test files, notes and the Reference Gerber Viewer to support users and especially developers of Gerber software.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The CAD systems then outputs PCB fabrication data to allow fabrication of the board.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The fabricator loads them into a computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) system to prepare data for each step of the PCB production process.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The .FileFunction attribute is the standardized method to link each layer in the PCB with its corresponding Gerber file in the fabrication data.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] If attributes are not supported, then only informal methods are available.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] A simple informal method is to express the file function clearly in the file name.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Sometimes the file extension is abused to indicate the file function - e.g. .BOT for the bottom layer rather than the standard extension .GBR.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In industry this is considered poor practice and engineers should use the appropriate X2 attribute instead.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] PCB Fabrication Data must comply with a number of rules: all layers must be aligned, a profile layer must be included, etc.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The CAD netlist can be embedded in the Gerber files.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] However, for historic reasons, netlists often are described in a separate file in IPC-D-356A, an electrical test format.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The material stack up, components and finishes are typically provided in informal text files or drawings.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In 2018 Ucamco has published a specification for an extension of the Gerber format to cover this fabrication documentation.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] RS-274X, extended Gerber or X-Gerber, was originally released in September 1998.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It consists of a stream of commands generating an ordered stream of graphics objects.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The graphics objects can be positive or negative.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Superimposed in the correct order they create the final image.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] A Gerber file contains the complete description of a PCB layer image without requiring any external files.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It has all the imaging operators needed for a PCB image.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Planes and pads can be specified without the need to paint or vector-fill as in Standard Gerber.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Released in February 2014, Gerber X2 adds additional metadata to the image.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Attributes allow adding metadata to a Gerber file.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Attributes are akin to labels providing information associated with image files, or features within them.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] For more information about attributes see X2 FAQ or intro video in the external links.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Fabrication documentation such as finish, overall thickness and materials is specified in a separate Gerber Job File.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The format specification is published at the official website.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It was already obsolete after the introduction of the much more capable Extended Gerber in 1998.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Standard Gerber was a numerical control (NC) format designed by Gerber Systems Corp to drive their vector photo plotters for the PCB industry in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It was a subset of the Electronic Industries Association RS-274-D specification, a format to drive mechanical NC machines in a wide range of industries.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It was widely used to drive vector plotters.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Standard Gerber was a simple ASCII format consisting of commands and XY coordinates.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] A Standard Gerber is an NC standard but not an image description standard: essential image information such the coordinate unit and the *apertures* definitions are not standardized.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] (Apertures are the basic shapes, similar to fonts in a PDF file.) They are described in a free-format sidecar text file intended for human reading, called an *aperture file* or a *wheel file*.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The sender and receiver have to agree on their meaning case-by-case.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Standard Gerber supports only the simple imaging operators that a vector plotter is capable of - drawing tracks and flashing apertures.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This is insufficient for efficient PCB fabrication data.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Copper pours must be created by *painting* (aka *stroking* or *vector-filling*) them with a vast number of tracks.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] All but the simplest pads are also painted because of the cost creating a corresponding physical aperture.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Painting creates the intended image but results in very large files that take long time to process and need error-prone manual work in CAM.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] (An aperture wheel is a rotating disk on which physical apertures are mounted, and by rotating the wheel the photoplotter selects the aperture to use.) Standard Gerber is not suitable for automated data transfer between PCB designers and manufacturers.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The Gerber file format is named after Joseph Gerber, an entrepreneur and inventor who pioneered vector photoplotters.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In 1980 Gerber Systems Corp. published the first edition of the *Gerber Format: a subset of EIA RS-274-D; plot data format reference book*, a subset of EIA RS-274-D it used to drive their line of vector photoplotters.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This format became known as Standard Gerber and was adopted by several other photoplotter vendors.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Standard Gerber became the de facto standard image format for PCB fabrication.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In 1991 with the availability of the more capable raster photoplotters, the Gerber format was extended with polygon areas and "mass parameters".
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] These allow the user to dynamically define apertures of different shapes and sizes, as well as defining polygon area fills without the need for "painting".
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It became a superset of RS-274-D standard Gerber.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The impetus to develop mass parameters was provided by AT&T.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This created a family of input formats, each one dedicated to a specific Gerber plotter model.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In April 1998 Gerber Systems Corp. was taken over by Barco ETS, Barco's PCB division, which is now called Ucamco.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In September 1998 Ucamco published the *RS-274X Format User's Guide*, a specification which unified the family of formats to a single image format, revoking a large number of model-specific constructs.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The format became known as Extended Gerber or GerberX.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Extended Gerber quickly superseded Standard Gerber as the *de facto* standard for PCB image data.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This became the de facto image standard for the PCB industry.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It is sometimes called "the backbone of the electronics industry".
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In the course of 2012 the format was comprehensively reviewed in *the great reform*.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] A representative library of 10,000 files from all over the world was investigated to establish current practice.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Constructs that were rarely or never used were deprecated.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Constructs with unclear interpretations were clarified.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The specification document was re-organized and its quality improved.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This resulted in revision I1 to I4 of the specification, published from December 2012 on.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The result was a simple, but powerful format, focused on the current needs of the PCB industry.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This version of the Gerber format was developed by Karel Tavernier and Rik Breemeersch from Ucamco.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In June 2013 Ucamco published a proposal to add three new commands to the Gerber format which allow inclusion of image attributes conveying metadata attached to the image and its components.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It invited feedback from the Gerber users before committing these ideas to a firm specification.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This process resulted in revision J1 in February 2014, updated with further revisions until revision 2015.07.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Including metadata adds intelligence to the format.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It converts a mere image description format to a full-fledged PCB data transfer format.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This is called *the second extension* and results what is known as *Gerber X2*, Gerber X1 being the pure image format.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Gerber X2 is fully backward compatible with X1, as the attributes do not affect the image.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Gerber X2 was developed by Karel Tavernier, Ludek Brukner and Thomas Weyn.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In September 2014 Ucamco revoked Standard Gerber.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In August 2015 Ucamco published a draft specification adding nested step and repeat and block apertures to make panel descriptions more efficient, calling for comments from the user community.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The final specification was published in November 2016 after substantial input.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] This revision was developed by Karel Tavernier and Rik Breemeersch.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Shortly afterwards the Cuprum Gerber viewer developed the first implementation.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In July 2016 Ucamco published a draft specification to include netlist information in Gerber, calling for input from the user community.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] After a number of revisions of the draft triggered by input from users, the draft was finalized on 2 October 2016.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In March 2017 Ucamco published a draft specification to include fabrication documentation in Gerber calling for input from the user community.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] There was a lively discussion, the draft went through seven public revisions before being finalized early April 2018.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In June 2017 a free online *Reference Gerber Viewer* was made available by Ucamco as a complement to the specification.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] It is updated with new functionality from time to time.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] In October 2019 Ucamco published a draft specification to include component information in Gerber data, calling for comments from the user community.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The proposal re-uses existing syntax and hence is backward compatible.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Although it does not introduce new syntax it extends Gerber into a new domain, and the name Gerber X3 is suggested.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] The draft specification was developed by Karel Tavernier.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Over the years there have been several attempts to replace Gerber by formats containing more information than just the layer image, e.g. netlist or component information.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] None of these attempts have been widely accepted within the electronics manufacturing industry, probably because the formats are complex.
[src:gb/gb-file-extension] Gerber remains the most widely used data transfer format.
[src:gb/gb] The domain was introduced with RFC 920 in October 1984 that set out the creation of ccTLD generally using country codes derived from the corresponding two-letter code in the ISO 3166-1 list.
[src:gb/gb] However, the .uk domain had been created separately a few months before the compilation of this list.
[src:gb/gb] Consequently, .gb was never widely used.
[src:gb/gb] It is no longer possible to register under this domain.
[src:gb/gb] .gb was used for a number of years, mainly by British government organisations and commercial e-mail services using X.400-based e-mail infrastructure.
[src:gb/gb] This simplified translating between DNS domains and X.400 addresses, which used "GB" as a country code.
[src:gb/gb] With the demise of X.400 e-mail and IANA's general aim of one TLD per country, use of .gb declined; the domain remains in existence, but it is not currently open to new domain registrations.
[src:gb/gb] As of 2025, there are at least three subdomains resolving through DNS (although none serve a web page or use): `hermes.dra.hmg.gb`, `delos.dra.hmg.gb`, and `dfhnet.dra.hmg.gb`.
[src:gb/gb] They were originally owned by the Defence Research Agency, which became the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency in 1995 and was split into QinetiQ and the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory in 2001; the websites became defunct some time thereafter.
[src:gb/gb] As of November 2022, Central Digital and Data Office's intention was to inform ICANN early in 2023 that the UK wishes to retire the .gb ccTLD.
